ledge in the areas of science, medicine, and engineering. Where possible, they provide concrete examples of how taking gender into account has yielded new research results and sparked creativity, opening new avenues for future research. Several government granting agencies, such as the National Institutes of Health and the European Commission, now require that requests for funding address whether, and in what sense, sex and gender are relevant to the objectives and methodologies of the research proposed, yet few research scientists or engineers know how to do gender analysis. This book begins to rectify the situation by shedding light on the how and the why.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBallard, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButovitsch Temm, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConkey, Margaret W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCórdova, France A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortmann, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHager, Lori D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwan, Mei-Po, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaVaque-Manty, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Sarah S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosser, Sue V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiebinger, Londa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiebinger, Londa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSperling, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc